text: People keep saying that there is no god just because the big bang happened. I believe in God just not the exact story of the Bible. I believe a God created everything however I do not believe it was done in 7 days. I believe God chose to shape the earth through the Big bang and all this took millions of years. Then God let the world develop on it's own.Thus evolution is true. I believe Jesus was a good man that was crucified. Not everything said in the Bible could have happened yet I like the message of the book. Be Kind to your fellow neighbors. As for the matter of if there is a heaven or not. It does not matter. I choose to believe that there is something after death. If there is something then I win and I will go there when I die. And if there is nothing after death and we just cease to exist then who am I to complain? I won't exist. Either way it's a win win situation. I am a normal guy unlike those nutbars that keep telling athiests that they are idiots and going to hell just because they don't believe in Jesus. Athiests are cool too. My best friend is an athiest yet she is a vegetarian and an environmentalist. I go to church every sunday and you know what I do? I sleep half of the time. If there was no christianity there would be no christmas or easter. Even athiests put up a tree during christmas go outside and play in the snow just like everyone else. They may not celebrate it for Jesus but still it brings their families together. Maybe we need a little bit of wonder in our lives. If I knew everything to be of scientific origin then where is the fun in that? Sometimes it's nice to believe in something else.

Make the world a better place because that makes you a good member of the human race, not because you will be rewarded/punished in an afterlife. text: I would just like to point out that no TV series or movie is ever going to be 100% accurate, unless human beings suddenly find a way to stop being subjective, which I don't think is going to happen anytime soon. Jesus may or may not have been white. That isn't particularly important. What is important is the message the series is trying to convey. Too many people are stuck around the idea that imagery is the most important aspect, but it isn't. I think this movie (which is basically just clips from The Bible miniseries, btw) has good intentions in spreading the importance and meaningfulness of the Bible. The movie will not be 100% accurate, I expect that. However, if you are looking for  Biblical accuracy, then READ THE BIBLE.

text: Go clarify, Jesus was a Nazarene, not a Nazirite.   Nazarene, as in he came from Nazareth.   Nazirite and Nazarene are two different things.  Nazirites have long hair - Bible does not say Jesus was a Nazarene, thus he would have no reason to have long hair.   Samson was a Nazarite. It was his long hair that was the secret to his power.  Nazirite means "One Singled Out". Those that had taken the Nazarite vow had 3 principal restrictions including: (1) They were to drink no intoxicating beverage; neither were they to eat any product of the grapevine, whether unripe, ripe, or dried, nor drink any of its juice, whether in the fresh, fermented, or vinegar state. (2) They were not to cut the hair of their heads. (3) They were not to touch a dead body, even that of the closest relative—father, mother, brother, or sister.—Nu 6:1-7.

text: Normally, Jesus movies don't appeal to me because it feels like someone is preaching me the bible. But I really am looking forward to this from both a religious and movie-goer point of view. I really love how this Jesus is portrayed. He's a lively and charmastic man we could relate to and learn about our humanity, hopes, and dreams. Even if this wasn't a movie about Jesus, I would still watch it because the actor does an excellent job in emitting a fresh-but-humbled energy. Most Jesus movies portray him so seriously it's hard to see him as 'one of us'. Those films usually focus on his death and resurrection. Here, this movie seems to explore the life he lived and the people he loved. He's as human as you and me, but obviously special. It seems fitting to see this type of movie since, to be honest, we have all seen stories that have borrowed from the story of Christ. These films showcase 'The One' who will save the human race through sacrifice and hope, whether it's Neo from the Matrix or Superman. Having written that, I think this is a movie that can be appreciated by both the religious AND non religious groups. Just my two cents, at least. ;)

Told with the scope and scale of an action epic, the film features powerful performances, exotic locales, dazzling visual effects and a rich orchestral score from Oscar®-winner Hans Zimmer. Portuguese actor Diogo Morgado portrays Jesus as the film spans from his humble birth through his teachings, crucifixion and ultimate resurrection. It marks the first motion picture about Jesus’ life since Passion of the Christ, released ten years ago.

text: "In the Beginning was THE WORD. And THE WORD was with God and THE WORD was God."  "The" Implies a singular term, and by translating THE WORD to Latin, we get Uni (One)  Verse (Word).  "In the Beginning was Uni Verse. And Uni Verse was with God and Uni Verse was God."  You see? The Bible mentions the Big Bang.  Right after that it goes on to say:  "And God said 'Let there be Light' and there was Light."  What came out of the Big Bang?  Light!  What is everything made of according to "modern science"???  LIGHT!  Light (by which I mean the entire electro-magnetic spectrum) burst forth from an infinitely dense and small particle, forming gasses and dust which became galaxies and worlds, and ultimately the stuff from which life is made.  The Bible says "He stretches out the Heavens like a tent to dwell in". And it's true, space-time stretched out from the Big Bang to form a dwelling for all the things that would eventually dwell here.  Jesus said "In my Father's house are many mansions."  How do you fit 1 mansion inside a house, let alone many? If the house is Space, and the mansions are Planets, then it makes perfect sense.  The angel said "Why do you marvel? This same Jesus whom you saw ascend into Heaven will return in the same way."  This was said after Jesus ascended into a "Bright Cloud", the same kind of "Bright Cloud" that was seen above Him at his Baptism, and the same "Cloud" that led Moses and his people in the desert, "a cloud by day and a pillar of fire by night".  In the abduction case of Betty and Barney Hill, the first UFO abduction to publicly mention "greys", the Hills said that when they questioned the aliens about religion, they got the impression that the "aliens" worshiped the UniVerse itself.  If they were "fallen angels" then it might explain why the aliens admit to worshiping the Uni-Verse, but refuse to call Him by name. YESHUA HA MASHIAC!

text: It kills me that the first response I see is regarding race. Have we progressed at all in 2000 years? But since the physicality of the actor is so important I will put all your minds at ease. Jesus was of middle eastern origin. The Middle East is referred to as "Asia Minor" because it is on the asian continent and genetically the people are asian. text: Some food for thought.  For centuries men have argued over whether a Jesus of Nazareth existed and still we have not reached a consensus, but it’s submitted that no man can argue that if every person emulated this man’s character (real or otherwise) in our daily lives, we would be a far more happier, peaceful and caring civilization with less problems.  Humans have such incredible potential and can be so wise, but yet can be confounded by such simple truths and principles.  The world would rather emulate celebrities, singers, other high profile and questionable characters and things.  It’s troubling and saddening that actors who “portray” doctors in film and television are idolized and worshipped, while the “real life” doctors quietly go about saving the lives of our loved ones and ourselves unnoticed and unappreciated. What have we become.  It could be said that we’ve become such a negative, greedy and jealous people, constantly trying to find fault with one another, engaging in all manner of deception and envying the possessions or position of another.  The laws that God adheres to and the process by which an individual goes through to test the validity and truth of those laws is no different to the process an individual would go through when seeking a knowledge and testimony of any physical law that we know, such as electricity, physics, engineering etc.  The individual (1) studies the law (2) tests or applies the law in action, before (3) understanding and obtaining a knowledge (testimony) of how the law works.  We wouldn’t allow an individual who has never studied and obtained the required qualification and registration for an Engineer to give us a sermon or design our homes or buildings.  Nor should we take heed to anyone who has not seriously and genuinely studied, tested or applied God’s laws (and there are more than 10) and then come to a personal knowledge of their experience or expect that taking heed to anyone who has will result in a personal understanding and testimony for ourselves.  There are no shortcuts, each person must diligently pursue their own course to discover the truth.  Just as one person cannot be a proxy engineering student for another, thinking the other will receive the requisite knowledge and understanding by way of proxy.  It just doesn’t work.  A final point.  Whether a person believes in the laws that govern electricity or not doesn’t make the laws any less valid nor does it affect the consequences if a person misuses the laws.  One will still be electrocuted irrespective of belief.  The same can be said for our Heavenly Father’s eternal laws.  The only difference is, for the most part, the consequences are not as spontaneous as the laws that govern electricity or other physical laws (that would be too easy), but the consequences for misuse will follow irrespective of belief.

text: Jews practice the Old Law and reject the Divinity of Christ and the Trinity. The Church teaches the following about the cessation of the Old Law and about all who continue to observe it: Pope Eugene IV, Council of Florence, 1441, ex cathedra:  “The Holy Roman Church firmly believes, professes and teaches that the matter pertaining to the law of the Old Testament, the Mosaic law, which are divided into ceremonies, sacred rites, sacrifices, and sacraments, because they were established to signify something in the future, although they were suited to the divine worship at that time, after our Lord’s coming had been signified by them, ceased, and the sacraments of the New Testament began; and that whoever, even after the passion, placed hope in these matters of the law and submitted himself to them as necessary for salvation, as if faith in Christ could not save without them, sinned mortally. Yet it does not deny that after the passion of Christ up to the promulgation of the Gospel they could have been observed until they were believed to be in no way necessary for salvation; but after the promulgation of the Gospel it asserts that they cannot be observed without the loss of eternal salvation. All, therefore, who after that time [the promulgation of the Gospel] observe circumcision and the Sabbath and the other requirements of the law, the holy Roman Church declares alien to the Christian faith and not in the least fit to participate in eternal salvation.”  Pope Benedict XIV, Ex Quo Primum (# 61), March 1, 1756:  “The first consideration is that the ceremonies of the Mosaic Law were abrogated by the coming of Christ and that they can no longer be observed without sin after the promulgation of the Gospel.”

text: I just saw this movie in theaters. It was utterly fantastic. The scene where Simon Peter gets out of the boat in the storm at sea and walks towards Jesus was very powerful and well done. The acting was good in particular the actors who played Jesus, Simon Peter, and Judas.  Also the effects were really good, most notably in the sea storm and the resurrection. The violence of the Passion was not over done like I heard it was in "The Passion of the Christ". (Never saw "Passion" so I wouldn't know.)  There were a couple of inaccuracies in the movie, but they're so minor that if you don't know about them you'd never know they were even there. My sister actually caught one in the very beginning of the movie that I missed. These inaccuracies are so few and far between and minor that it shouldn't take you out of the movie even for a slight moment.  The audience I was in actually applauded the scene when Jesus appeared to his Apostles after his resurrection. Not unjustifiably so either. It was a very great scene.

text: I saw the movie.  I think it seemed to try and push a catholic doctrine, which is not biblical.  It tried to establish Peter as the first Pope, with the scene of Peter giving the disciples bread and wine.  Also, one of the disciples says to Peter, that he should not have abandoned Jesus because he was supposed to be the "rock".  They put those scenes in after Jesus is resurrected--Peter giving communion and being called the "rock" to try and tie in Catholicism (sneaky, sneaky!).  Lastly, the song at the end of the movie is "Mary Did You Know", which eludes to additional false doctrine practiced by Catholics of praying to Mary.   True salvation is putting your faith in Jesus alone for the forgiveness of your sin for the FINISHED work on the cross.  Communion is only to commemorate, remember what he did for you at the cross.  There is no purgatory, no praying to dead saints, no need to go to a priest for forgiveness of sins.  The thief on the cross gave the perfect example--I am a sinner and deserve death, you [Jesus] are perfect and innocent, as God in the flesh.  Please forgive me and remember me (receive me) in heaven...FAITH ALONE, CHRIST ALONE...Don't fall for the hype.  WHAT THE BIBLE SAYS YOU NEED TO BE SAVED ETERNALLY:  Ephesians 2:8-9 says, "For by grace are ye saved through faith; and that not of yourselves: it is the gift of God: Not of works, lest any man should boast.  " Romans 10:9-13 says,"That if thou shalt confess with thy mouth the Lord Jesus, and shalt believe in thine heart that God hath raised him from the dead, thou shalt be saved.

text: For those people who will claim that Christianity or Islam just be correct because there are billions of them but only 15 million Jews, I will say this: Imagine there are two groups of a thousand people and 50 people walking on the road and they go in two separate directions at a fork in the road.  One person who hadn't been part of that group reaches the fork and sees the two groups on the two different paths.  Logic would say that he should follow the path with more people because they must know the proper path out of the forest. But unbeknownst to him, the group of 1000 is made up of blind people with only 2 people who can see leading them, whereas the group of 50 people is made up of individuals who can all see.  Point: numbers means nothing, and the fact that both Christianity and Islam claim to be correct must mean that at least one of them is automatically wrong.

text: ***GIVE ME A BREAK! *** I questioned whether I should see this movie or not based on some reviews I read saying how the producers are new age and scripture is left out/ inaccurate. But I went to watch anyway after reading all Bob's pros list. I am so glad I did! I went with my husband and 4 kids and my husband, 10 yr old daughter, and I all cried. It was a beautiful portrayal of Jesus' character and main purpose and God's plan. The only thing that would have made it better would have been to include even more details but then the movie could have been up to 4 to 6 hours or longer! Everything can't be put into a 2 hr long movie. The parts that were biblically inaccurate weren't things that are fundamental doctrinal principles. If u are a born again Christian and u can sit all the way through that movie without being moved then your heart must be callous and u need to eat some humble pie or something. :) I didn't see any new age philosophy. I heard tons of scripture and a few things that were unexpectedly boldly written. I believe people can be drawn to Jesus with this movie. Remember, it's not a sermon. It's a movie for crying out loud

text: I want to say to everybody here: please be more understanding and be less arrogant. Think before you speak (metaphorically then) and question yourself first before questioning others. Learn to use logic in a correct way (atheists and theists alike) and ask yourself what you are trying to prove.   In my understanding not science nor religion are, but philosophy is the answer to life's most difficult problems. True understanding of reality (the one we experience, not the one we live in) comes from understanding our self. People tend to claim that some things in life (without really questioning the things, themselves or the one who poses them) must be true, because it was said or written by a person to whom they attain certain authority. To some he is either a god or a prophet, to others that person is a scientist, a teacher or a politician.   Modern creationists claim that a compilation of books (being the Bible) is a good base to deliver a correct argument that explains the workings of the world. They make two mistakes. The first is the obvious one, the one where they use the Bible as an authority to prove that the Bible is an authority. There must first be an act of belief before one can continue in this reasoning. The second one is the claim that we can actually really understand how the world works. It is a common mistake, still made by non-creationists as well.   Where is the prove that what we perceive is right and how we reason is correct? Isn't that a leap of faith too? I will point out two things: an illusion feels real but it remains an illusion. How can we know if our real perception isn't false, isn't an illusion? Second, a dream feels right and true when one dreams it, but wrong and irrational when one is awake. So it is possible to experience a completely different form of rationality, which is, when we are awake, not rational at all. Surely we cannot claim then that our awake logic is in fact more rational than our dream logic when we dream?   Some extreme non-believers have the tendency to state scientific facts as absolute truths without questioning them. They assume that what they learned at school, or what they heard from their friends or saw on televisions must be true. They attain a form of authority to a person, assuming that he isn't wrong. This is also an act of belief. A bad argument against this would be that scientists change their views when they are proven wrong. This is true (in theory) but the scientists who are proven wrong are the persons to whom authority is attained. They are not the persons who attain (well they obviously do in other cases). One can compare it with a creationist who never read the Bible but makes claims about it and about reality based on the findings and interpretations of others, who, he realises, could be wrong.   Another thing that is to be said on the subject of science is that most non-creationists believe, for instance, in the existence of black holes. Who has ever experienced the existence of a black hole? Yes one has seen photo's made by Hubble, depicting black holes. Are these photo's real? If so, what do they depict? One sees a black hole in the picture because one is told to. Then how can we be sure about anything? All we have is doubt. This is a subject which has been thoroughly researched in philosophy.   The Bible is, however, a part of our Western identity, it is a beautiful collection of stories, wisdom and lessons, but it is a book written by men for men. That does not make it worthless. The Hygienist movement in the 19th century was wrong to believe that filth is the origin of disease, yet understanding that their actions (removing filth and cleaning cities) have actually reduced diseases (because bacterial life flourished in such environments) should make you understand that our modern day assumptions, which we consider as true, could be wrong. It would be necessary to keep that in mind when claiming that other people are wrong and you are right. This does not make the Hygienist movement an utterly worthless movement in the eyes of history, they, in fact, really have had an impact and brought us partially to our understanding of diseases today (and saved people and cleaned our cities). Some people also make the mistake of looking at the past with an anachronistic view. They then imply a feeling of superiority over the past whilst claiming that those people in the past, who were then wrong according to their anachronistic view, should have respected people with other views in stead of burning them at the steak, whilst judging other people with other views themselves today.  Conclusion. We cannot know anything, the more we know the more we realise that what we know is nothing. We are not perfect and should not act like it. We are not a depiction of the divine and so isn't our reasoning. We are animals whose primary objective is to survive, not to understand. Realise this and act like this. Peace.  "One cannot doubt the fact that one doubts."   That's all folks :)

text: @ dahim-blackhell benyahia  God's intellect is indeed personified by the Son as is his love is personified by the Holy Spirit.....  "Accordingly we reply that the term person signifies nothing else but an individual substance of rational nature. And since under an individual substance of rational nature is contained the substance, individual, i.e. incommunicable and distinct from others, whether of God, of man or of angels, it follows that a divine Person must signify something subsistent and distinct in the divine nature, just as a human person signifies something subsistent and distinct in human nature: and this is the formal signification of a person whether divine or human. Since, however, that which is distinct and subsistent in human ‘nature is nothing else than something individualized and differentiated from others by individual matter, it follows that this is the material signification when we speak of a human person. But the only thing that is distinct and incommunicable in the divine nature is relation, since all that is absolute is common and undivided. Now in God relation is really the same as the essence. And as in God essence is identical with the one who has the essence (e.g. the Godhead is identical with God), so also is relation the same as the one who is related. Consequently relation is the same as that which is distinct and subsists in the divine nature. It is evident then that person commonly speaking signifies an individual substance of rational nature; while a divine person in its formal signification denotes a distinct being subsistent in the divine nature. And seeing that this can be nothing else but a relation or a relative being, it follows that in its material signification it denotes a relation or a relative being. Hence it may be said that it signifies a relation by way of substance not qua essence but qua hypostasis, even as it signifies a relation not qua relation but qua relative: e.g. as signifying Father not as signifying paternity. For in this way the signified relation is included indirectly in the signification of the divine Person, which is nothing but something distinct by a relation and subsistent in the divine essence"  Aquinas ( Quaestiones Disputatae De Potentiae Dei)....and so God to love perfectly must share his love perfectly in some aspect that is through the persons of God whereby in a spiration of procession God the father loves perfeclty God the Son through the spiration of the Holy SPirit which proceeds from both..since God cannot love himself perfectly since this is vanity and a sin God needs love a person perfectly as some other in relation but in substance must needs be perfect since God himself is perfect..we are imperfect and so God loves us but we cannot receive his perfection since we are potentiated by him....

He said, "Thus [it will be]; your Lord says, 'It is easy for Me, and We will make him a sign to the people and a mercy from Us. And it is a matter [already] decreed.' " So she conceived him, and she withdrew with him to a remote place. And the pains of childbirth drove her to the trunk of a palm tree. She said, "Oh, I wish I had died before this and was in oblivion, forgotten." But he called her from below her, "Do not grieve; your Lord has provided beneath you a stream. And shake toward you the trunk of the palm tree; it will drop upon you ripe, fresh dates. So eat and drink and be contented. And if you see from among humanity anyone, say, 'Indeed, I have vowed to the Most Merciful abstention, so I will not speak today to [any] man.' " Then she brought him to her people, carrying him. They said, "O Mary, you have certainly done a thing unprecedented. O sister of Aaron, your father was not a man of evil, nor was your mother unchaste." So she pointed to him. They said, "How can we speak to one who is in the cradle a child?" [Jesus] said, "Indeed, I am the servant of Allah . He has given me the Scripture and made me a prophet. And He has made me blessed wherever I am and has enjoined upon me prayer and zakah as long as I remain alive And [made me] dutiful to my mother, and He has not made me a wretched tyrant.And peace is on me the day I was born and the day I will die and the day I am raised alive." That is Jesus, the son of Mary - the word of truth about which they are in dispute. It is not [befitting] for Allah to take a son; exalted is He! When He decrees an affair, He only says to it, "Be," and it is. [Jesus said], "And indeed, Allah is my Lord and your Lord, so worship Him. That is a straight path." Next, it is not untrue that Jesus in the modern world bears significance to Cesare Borgia of whom Jesus was painted in the image of Cesare, of whom was an unscrupulous and evil Italian state prince during the Renaissance.    Therefore, a lot of our perceptions of Jesus is wrong and we need to cut out these visual occult imagery.  The only way to Jesus is by faith.  Remember St Paul and then re emphasized by Martin Luther that we are justified by faith alone?  Therfore if you have faith in Jesus, if you believe all of his teachings and follow his Words, and pursue and prioritize Jesus first place in our lives as God, we are saved and will enjoy relationship with our loving Father.  The rest about seeking prosperity and healing is just secondary and should never come first place to seeking the Lord.  Please do not fall into the trap of modern day Christianity of humanism.

text: Putting aside all the theological differences and arguments that are here on this page because i could easily get wrapped in it, Jesus is the Savior of man...theological differences and arguments fall short of the simplicity of the Cross and a changed life....I can testify to this as many many Christians can as well....Do you think that when someone is healed or raised from the dead they ask-"Jesus, why did you do this and how many times do i need to thank you?" or something of that nature?  The answer is no...we don't need to question why but just accept it...Love that is done from the heart needs no "Who, what, where when or why?"  "Love does not envy, it does not boast, etc."....it's very simple...Jesus died for our sin, rose again to prove his power of death, hell and the grave, and is coming back again soon....That is why his LOVE is Eternal, it is FINAL, filled with mercy...Our merciful God paid the price for you, me and everyone...Look at it this way....The Bible says that the "wages of sin is death".  True statement.  We deserve death but Jesus took our place, he became the exchange for the ETERNAL change in our life...Indeed, God is good, all the time.  We have much to rejoice and be glad in when it comes to Jesus so much that I couldn't possibly explain, show or do humanly to put finality and closure to the gratitude i have for the Son of God....I don't know.  I think that's why there is a Christian song with the lyric "Indescribable, uncontainable".  Jesus and all he stood for IS indescribable and LOVE is the center of this indescribable God-man.  I'm LIVING proof of a changed life thru Jesus Christ.  I make alot of mistakes, yes i'll share that on youtube.  But the Bible says this, "Being confident of this, that he who began a good work in you will carry it on to completion until the day of Christ Jesus." Luke 22:7 Then came the day of Unleavened Bread on which the Passover lamb had to be sacrificed. 8 Jesus sent Peter and John, saying, “Go and make preparations for us to eat the Passover.” 11 and say to the owner of the house, ‘The Teacher asks: Where is the guest room, where I may eat the Passover with my disciples?’ 12 He will show you a large room upstairs, all furnished. Make preparations there.” 13 They left and found things just as Jesus had told them. So they prepared the Passover. 15 And he said to them, “I have eagerly desired to eat this Passover with you before I suffer.  The video goes to great lengths to disguise the fact that the Last Supper was in fact the Passover as the 13th day of the month came to a close, they ate the Passover on the evening of the 14th after the sun had set.  Even unto this very day, the traditional jews keep Passover on the 15th after the 14th day sunset. text: JESUS in the QURAN   The Islamic view of Jesus lies between two extremes. The Jews , who rejected Jesus as a Prophet of God, called him an impostor. The Christians, on the other hand, considered him to be the son of God and worship him as such. Islam considers Jesus to be one of the great prophets of God and respects him as much as Ibrahim (Abraham), Moses, and Mohammed. (Peace Be Upon Them) This is conformity with the Islamic view of the oneness of God, the oneness of Divine guidance, and the complementary role of the subsequent mission of God's messengers. The essence of Islam - willing submission to the will of God - was revealed to Adam, who was passed it on to his children. All following revelations to Noah, Ibrahim, Moses, Jesus, and finally Mohammed (Peace Be Upon Them) were conformity with that message, with some elaboration to define the revelation between man and God, man and man, man and instructions. Thus, any contradictions among revealed religions is viewed by Islam as a man-made element introduced into these religions. The position of Jesus in the three major religions - Judaism, Christianity, and Islam - should not be an exception. Although the Quran does not present a detailed life-story of Jesus, it highlights the important aspects of his birth, his mission, his ascension to heaven, and passes judgements on the Christian beliefs concerning him. The Quranic account of Jesus starts with the conception of his mother, Mary, whose mother, the wife of Imran, vowed to dedicate her child to the service of God in the temple. When Mary became a woman, the Holy Spirit (the Archangel Gabriel) appeared to her as a man bringing her news of a son. We read the following dialogue in the Quran between Mary and the Angel: "When the angel said, "Mary, god gives you a good tidings of a Word from Him whose **** is messiah, Jesus, son of Mary, -high honoured shall he be in this world and the next, near stationed to God. He shall speak to men in the cradle, and of age, and righteous he shall be, "lord" said Mary "How shall I have a son, seeing no mortal has touched me? "Even so, he said "God creates what He will". When he decrees a thing He but say to it, "Be", and it is. (Al-Imran 3:45-47) In a chapter (Surah) entitled "Maryam" (Mary), the Quran tells us how Mary gave birth to her son, and how the Jesus accused her when she brought the child home: "Then she brought the child to her folk, carrying him, and they said, "Mary, you have surely committed a monstrous thing. Sister of Aaron, your father was not a wicked man, nor your mother a woman unchaste. Mary pointed to the child; but they said, 'Hoe shall we speak to one who still in the cradle, a little child. And he said, 'Lo, I am God's servant, God has given me the Book and made me a Prophet Blessed He has made me ,wherever/may be; and hi has enjoined me to prayer, and to give the alms so long as I live, and likewise to cherish my mother; He has not made me arrogant and wicked. Peace be upon me, the day I was born, and the day I die, and the day I am raised up a live. "Maryam 19:29-33) in the same chapter, following the above quotation, God assures Mohammed (PBUH) and through him the whole world, that what is told above is the TRUTH about Jesus (PBUH), although Christians might not accept it. Jesus is NOT the son of God: He was obviously enough, the son of Mary. The verses continue: "That is Jesus, son of Mary, in word of truth, concerning which they are doubting. It is not for God to take a son unto Him. Glory be to Him, He nut says to it, 'Be, and it is. (Maryam 19:34-35) After this strong statement about the nature of Jesus, God directed Mohammed (PBUH) to call the Christians to worship the one God: "Surely God is my God, and your God, so surely serve him. This is the straight path". (Maryam 19:36) The rejection of the very idea of God having a son is restated later in the same chapter with even stronger words: "And they say, The All-merciful has taken unto Himself a son. You have indeed advanced something hideous. As if the skies are about to burst, the earth to split asunder and its mountain to fall down in the utter ruin for that they have attributed to the All-merciful a son; and behaves not the All-merciful to take a son. None there in the heavens and earth but comes to the All-merciful as a servant" (Maryam 19:88-93) The Quran recognizes the fact that Jesus had no human father, but this does not make him the son of God, or God himself. By this criterion, Adam would have been more entitled more entitled to be the son of God, because he had neither a father nor a mother, so the Quran draws attention to the miraculous creation of both in the following verses; " truly the likeness of Jesus, in God's sight is as Adam's likeness; He created him of dust, then He said upon him, 'Be' and hi was. (Al-Imran 3:59) The Quran rejects the concept of Trinity God the Father, God the son, God the Holy Spirit - as strongly as it rejects the concept of Jesus as the son of God. This is because GOD IS ONE. Three cannot be one. The Quran addresses Christians in the following verses from the Surrah entitled "An-Nisaa" (The Women) People of the Book, do not go beyond the bounds in your religion, and say nought as to God but the Truth. The messiah, Jesus, son of Mary, was only the messenger of God, and his word (Fulfilment of his word (Fulfilment of His command, through the word "Be", for the creation of Jesus) that he committed to Mary, and a spirit originating from Him (was given life by God). So believe in God and His Messengers, and say not 'Three'. Refrain, better is for you. God is only one God. Glory be to him-that He should have a son! To Him belongs all that is in the Heavens and in the Earth; God suffices for a guardian. The Messiah will not disdain to be a servant of God, neither the Angels who are close to Him. Whosoever disdains to serve Him and walks proud, He will assuredly muster them to Him, all of them. As for the believers, who do deeds of righteousness, we will pay them their rewards in full, and He will give them more, of His bounty; as for them who disdain and walks proud, then He will punish with a severe punishment, and they shall not find for them, apart from God, a friend or helper." (An-Nissa 4:171-173) The denial of Jesus's divinity (and. For the matter, of Mary's divinity) is presented in the Quran in the form of a dialogue, at the Day of Judgement, between the Almighty Jesus. All the Messengers and their nations will gather before God and He will ask the Messengers how they were received by their people and what they said to them. Among those who will be questioned is Jesus: "And when God said, 'O Jesus, son of Mary, did you say unto men, "Take me and my mother as gods, apart from God"? He said, 'To you be glory! It is not mine to say what I have no right to. If I indeed said it, you would have known it, knowing what is within my heart, though I do not know your knowledge; you know the things unseen. I only said to them what you did commands me: "Serve God, my God and your God." (Al-Maida 5-116) Given that the Quran denies the Trinity and the son ship of Jesus, what, according to the Quran, was the real mission of Jesus? The answer is that Jesus was a link in a long chain of Prophets and Messengers sent by God to various nations and societies whenever they needed guidance or deviated from his teachings of Moses and other Messengers. As he was miraculously supported by numerous miracles to prove that he was a Messengers from God. However, the majority of the Jews rejected his ministry. In another verse of the Quran, Jesus confirmed the validity of the Torah which was revealed to Moses, and also conveyed he glad tidings of a final Messenger who follow him: "And when Jesus son of Mary said, 'Children of Israel, I am indeed the Messenger to you, confirming the Torah that is before me, and giving good tiding of a Messenger who shall be the praised one."(As-Saff 61:6) Note that "praised one" is a translation of "Ahmad" - The Prophet Mohammed's ****. Careful study of the New Testament shows that Jesus refers to the same Prophet in John 14:16-17: "And I will give you another Counsellor (ThProphet Mohammed). To be with you for ever, even the Spirit of Truth." The usual explanation of this Prophecy is that the counsellor referred to is the Holy Spirit, but this explanation is excluded by a previous verse in John: "Nevertheless I tell you the truth: it is to your advantage that I go away, for if I do not go away, the Counsellor will not come to you." The characteristics of this counsellor, as can be derived from the prophecy, are that he will stay forever with the believers, he will glorify Jesus; and he will speak that he hears form God. All four characteristics apply to the Prophet Mohammed. He came six centuries after Jesus. He came six centuries after Jesus. He came with a universal and everlasting message, fulfilling the prophecy that the counsellor will stay forever with the faithful. He glorified Jesus as a great Prophet. The Quran attributes to Jesus miracles not mentioned in the Bible's Old and New Testaments, as well as specific verses in the Quran show how the Prophet Mohammad is rejected by Jews and Christians out of prejudice and misunderstanding, rather that carefully study the Bible. It is a sad fact of history that not many are following the "straight path" to which people were called by Jesus. He was only followed by a few disciples inspired by God to support him. The non-believers plotted - as they would against Mohammed, six centuries later - to kill Jesus. But God had better plan for him and his followers, as the Quran tells us: "And when Jesus perceived their unbelief, he said 'Who will be my helpers in the cause of God?The apostles said, 'we are Gods helpers. We believe in God; so bear witness of our submission God, we believe in that you have sent down, and we follow the Messenger. Inscribe us therefore with those who bear witness. 'And they devised, and God devised, and God devised, and God is the best of divisors. When God said, 'Jesus, I will take you to Me and will raise you to Me, and I will purify you (of the falsehoods) of those who do not believe. I will make your followers above the unbelievers till the Resurrection Day."(Al-Imran 3:52-55) As the above verses indicate, Jesus was taken and raised to heaven. He was not crucified. It was certainly the plan of the enemies of Jesus to put him to death on the cross, but God saved him and someone else was crucified: "And for their unbelief, and their uttering against Mary a grave false charge, and for their saying, 'We killed the messiah, Jesus son of Mary, the Messiah of God"…yet they did not slay him, neither crucified him, only a likeness of that was shown to them. Those who are at variance concerning him are surely in doubt the following of conjecture; and they did not kill him of certainty…no indeed; God raised him up to Him; God is Almighty, Allwise. There is not one of the people of the book but will assuredly believe him before his death, and on the Resurrection Day he will be a witness against them." (An-Nissa 4:156-159) The Quran does not explain who was the person crucified instead of Jesus, nor elaborate on the Second Coming of Jesus. However, explanators of the Quran have always interpreted the last verse of the above quotation to mean that Jesus will believe in him before he dies. This understanding is supported by authentic sayings (Hadith) of the Prophet Mohammed may the peace and blessings of Allah him and upon all His Messengers

text: I was very wrong in my way of thinking. There was a moment in my life where I did not believe in God. Then I started having dreams and God showed me, through them, what the truth was. I had visions; for a moment I thought I was going crazy because I was seeing things I had never seen before. Now, not only am I positive that God exists, but I know where God is. He is in all of us, with no discrimination. He loves us all equally, no matter who we are or what religion we practice. We are one. For more explanations in regards to my comments, read the book Unify. It was released this month. While writing the book, I used the Bible, Quran, and Torah in order to back up what I am saying in the book. I read those books on purpose because I do not want to mislead anyone. If anyone wants to prove me wrong, please read the book and I am willing, if I am wrong, to accept that I am wrong. I will give you your money back and I will apologize to you. In the book Unify, on page 120, it explains how Jesus says in John 14:19 how we are one and for the people who still believe Jesus will come back, I am not saying this, Jesus said it himself that the world will not see him anymore.. This is what he said "Before long, the world will not see me anymore, but you will see me, Because I live, you will also live. On that day you will realize that I am in my Father, and you are in me, and I am in you." Please read your book like a logo with hidden images. If you are reading the Bible, concentrate on Jesus and Moses. If you read the Quran, concentrate on what Muhammad said. If you are reading the Torah, concentrate on Abraham. text: Regardless of whether or not you believe in God, the Bible is a rather well-written book. Among my favorites include East of Eden, The Catcher in the Rye, and The Holy Bible. I am not kidding, it really is a great book. Also, I admit to being Catholic, however I cannot stand when individuals try to prove that the beliefs of atheists and agnostics are wrong. In my opinion, there is no "wrong" in believing whatever you want. With that being said, I also have no respect for individuals who try and prove that God does't exist. It is illogical to make a true claim stating that "God is real" because the premises may no be true. However at the same time, it is also illogical to state that "God is not real" solely because there may not be proof that he is real.   Anyways, just like any other movie that was inspired by a book, I'm excited to see this.

text: JESUS in the QURAN   The Islamic view of Jesus lies between two extremes. The Jews , who rejected Jesus as a Prophet of God, called him an impostor. The Christians, on the other hand, considered him to be the son of God and worship him as such. Islam considers Jesus to be one of the great prophets of God and respects him as much as Ibrahim (Abraham), Moses, and Mohammed. (Peace Be Upon Them) This is conformity with the Islamic view of the oneness of God, the oneness of Divine guidance, and the complementary role of the subsequent mission of God's messengers. The essence of Islam - willing submission to the will of God - was revealed to Adam, who was passed it on to his children. All following revelations to Noah, Ibrahim, Moses, Jesus, and finally Mohammed (Peace Be Upon Them) were conformity with that message, with some elaboration to define the revelation between man and God, man and man, man and instructions. Thus, any contradictions among revealed religions is viewed by Islam as a man-made element introduced into these religions. The position of Jesus in the three major religions - Judaism, Christianity, and Islam - should not be an exception. Although the Quran does not present a detailed life-story of Jesus, it highlights the important aspects of his birth, his mission, his ascension to heaven, and passes judgements on the Christian beliefs concerning him. The Quranic account of Jesus starts with the conception of his mother, Mary, whose mother, the wife of Imran, vowed to dedicate her child to the service of God in the temple. When Mary became a woman, the Holy Spirit (the Archangel Gabriel) appeared to her as a man bringing her news of a son. We read the following dialogue in the Quran between Mary and the Angel: "When the angel said, "Mary, god gives you a good tidings of a Word from Him whose ** is messiah, Jesus, son of Mary, -high honoured shall he be in this world and the next, near stationed to God. He shall speak to men in the cradle, and of age, and righteous he shall be, "lord" said Mary "How shall I have a son, seeing no mortal has touched me? "Even so, he said "God creates what He will". When he decrees a thing He but say to it, "Be", and it is. (Al-Imran 3:45-47) In a chapter (Surah) entitled "Maryam" (Mary), the Quran tells us how Mary gave birth to her son, and how the Jesus accused her when she brought the child home: "Then she brought the child to her folk, carrying him, and they said, "Mary, you have surely committed a monstrous thing. Sister of Aaron, your father was not a wicked man, nor your mother a woman unchaste. Mary pointed to the child; but they said, 'Hoe shall we speak to one who still in the cradle, a little child. And he said, 'Lo, I am God's servant, God has given me the Book and made me a Prophet Blessed He has made me ,wherever/may be; and hi has enjoined me to prayer, and to give the alms so long as I live, and likewise to cherish my mother; He has not made me arrogant and wicked. Peace be upon me, the day I was born, and the day I die, and the day I am raised up a live. "Maryam 19:29-33) in the same chapter, following the above quotation, God assures Mohammed (PBUH) and through him the whole world, that what is told above is the TRUTH about Jesus (PBUH), although Christians might not accept it. Jesus is NOT the son of God: He was obviously enough, the son of Mary. The verses continue: "That is Jesus, son of Mary, in word of truth, concerning which they are doubting. It is not for God to take a son unto Him. Glory be to Him, He nut says to it, 'Be, and it is. (Maryam 19:34-35) After this strong statement about the nature of Jesus, God directed Mohammed (PBUH) to call the Christians to worship the one God: "Surely God is my God, and your God, so surely serve him. This is the straight path". (Maryam 19:36) The rejection of the very idea of God having a son is restated later in the same chapter with even stronger words: "And they say, The All-merciful has taken unto Himself a son. You have indeed advanced something hideous. As if the skies are about to burst, the earth to split asunder and its mountain to fall down in the utter ruin for that they have attributed to the All-merciful a son; and behaves not the All-merciful to take a son. None there in the heavens and earth but comes to the All-merciful as a servant" (Maryam 19:88-93) The Quran recognizes the fact that Jesus had no human father, but this does not make him the son of God, or God himself. By this criterion, Adam would have been more entitled more entitled to be the son of God, because he had neither a father nor a mother, so the Quran draws attention to the miraculous creation of both in the following verses; " truly the likeness of Jesus, in God's sight is as Adam's likeness; He created him of dust, then He said upon him, 'Be' and hi was. (Al-Imran 3:59) The Quran rejects the concept of Trinity God the Father, God the son, God the Holy Spirit - as strongly as it rejects the concept of Jesus as the son of God. This is because GOD IS ONE. Three cannot be one. The Quran addresses Christians in the following verses from the Surrah entitled "An-Nisaa" (The Women) People of the Book, do not go beyond the bounds in your religion, and say nought as to God but the Truth. The messiah, Jesus, son of Mary, was only the messenger of God, and his word (Fulfilment of his word (Fulfilment of His command, through the word "Be", for the creation of Jesus) that he committed to Mary, and a spirit originating from Him (was given life by God). So believe in God and His Messengers, and say not 'Three'. Refrain, better is for you. God is only one God. Glory be to him-that He should have a son! To Him belongs all that is in the Heavens and in the Earth; God suffices for a guardian. The Messiah will not disdain to be a servant of God, neither the Angels who are close to Him. Whosoever disdains to serve Him and walks proud, He will assuredly muster them to Him, all of them. As for the believers, who do deeds of righteousness, we will pay them their rewards in full, and He will give them more, of His bounty; as for them who disdain and walks proud, then He will punish with a severe punishment, and they shall not find for them, apart from God, a friend or helper." (An-Nissa 4:171-173) The denial of Jesus's divinity (and. For the matter, of Mary's divinity) is presented in the Quran in the form of a dialogue, at the Day of Judgement, between the Almighty Jesus. All the Messengers and their nations will gather before God and He will ask the Messengers how they were received by their people and what they said to them. Among those who will be questioned is Jesus: "And when God said, 'O Jesus, son of Mary, did you say unto men, "Take me and my mother as gods, apart from God"? He said, 'To you be glory! It is not mine to say what I have no right to. If I indeed said it, you would have known it, knowing what is within my heart, though I do not know your knowledge; you know the things unseen. I only said to them what you did commands me: "Serve God, my God and your God." (Al-Maida 5-116) Given that the Quran denies the Trinity and the son ship of Jesus, what, according to the Quran, was the real mission of Jesus? The answer is that Jesus was a link in a long chain of Prophets and Messengers sent by God to various nations and societies whenever they needed guidance or deviated from his teachings of Moses and other Messengers. As he was miraculously supported by numerous miracles to prove that he was a Messengers from God. However, the majority of the Jews rejected his ministry. In another verse of the Quran, Jesus confirmed the validity of the Torah which was revealed to Moses, and also conveyed he glad tidings of a final Messenger who follow him: "And when Jesus son of Mary said, 'Children of Israel, I am indeed the Messenger to you, confirming the Torah that is before me, and giving good tiding of a Messenger who shall be the praised one."(As-Saff 61:6) Note that "praised one" is a translation of "Ahmad" - The Prophet Mohammed's **. Careful study of the New Testament shows that Jesus refers to the same Prophet in John 14:16-17: "And I will give you another Counsellor (ThProphet Mohammed). To be with you for ever, even the Spirit of Truth." The usual explanation of this Prophecy is that the counsellor referred to is the Holy Spirit, but this explanation is excluded by a previous verse in John: "Nevertheless I tell you the truth: it is to your advantage that I go away, for if I do not go away, the Counsellor will not come to you." The characteristics of this counsellor, as can be derived from the prophecy, are that he will stay forever with the believers, he will glorify Jesus; and he will speak that he hears form God. All four characteristics apply to the Prophet Mohammed. He came six centuries after Jesus. He came six centuries after Jesus. He came with a universal and everlasting message, fulfilling the prophecy that the counsellor will stay forever with the faithful. He glorified Jesus as a great Prophet. The Quran attributes to Jesus miracles not mentioned in the Bible's Old and New Testaments, as well as specific verses in the Quran show how the Prophet Mohammad is rejected by Jews and Christians out of prejudice and misunderstanding, rather that carefully study the Bible. It is a sad fact of history that not many are following the "straight path" to which people were called by Jesus. He was only followed by a few disciples inspired by God to support him. The non-believers plotted - as they would against Mohammed, six centuries later - to kill Jesus. But God had better plan for him and his followers, as the Quran tells us: "And when Jesus perceived their unbelief, he said 'Who will be my helpers in the cause of God?The apostles said, 'we are Gods helpers. We believe in God; so bear witness of our submission God, we believe in that you have sent down, and we follow the Messenger. Inscribe us therefore with those who bear witness. 'And they devised, and God devised, and God devised, and God is the best of divisors. When God said, 'Jesus, I will take you to Me and will raise you to Me, and I will purify you (of the falsehoods) of those who do not believe. I will make your followers above the unbelievers till the Resurrection Day."(Al-Imran 3:52-55) As the above verses indicate, Jesus was taken and raised to heaven. He was not crucified. It was certainly the plan of the enemies of Jesus to put him to death on the cross, but God saved him and someone else was crucified: "And for their unbelief, and their uttering against Mary a grave false charge, and for their saying, 'We killed the messiah, Jesus son of Mary, the Messiah of God"…yet they did not slay him, neither crucified him, only a likeness of that was shown to them. Those who are at variance concerning him are surely in doubt the following of conjecture; and they did not kill him of certainty…no indeed; God raised him up to Him; God is Almighty, Allwise. There is not one of the people of the book but will assuredly believe him before his death, and on the Resurrection Day he will be a witness against them." (An-Nissa 4:156-159) The Quran does not explain who was the person crucified instead of Jesus, nor elaborate on the Second Coming of Jesus. However, explanators of the Quran have always interpreted the last verse of the above quotation to mean that Jesus will believe in him before he dies. This understanding is supported by authentic sayings (Hadith) of the Prophet Mohammed may the peace and blessings of Allah him and upon all His Messengers

text: So I skimmed through the comments a bit and I noticed the percentage of them were religion-related. I, as an Agnostic, truthfully think this is an amazing movie. The setting, the feeling it gives off, everything about it was just good. I didn't look at it on a religious perspective and I think it'd be stupid to look at it that way. Appreciate the movie for what it is, not the religious views involved in it. I understand where you may be coming from if you're Christian, because this movie is based off of the Christian Bible. So I can see where you'd be even more hyped for the movie over other religions. It brings your beliefs to life, to give you a visual perspective of the Bible. As regards to other religions though, if you didn't enjoy the movie and only intend on arguing about religion, don't be ignorant and argue about it. This applies to Christians as well.  /Just enjoy the movie\

As the writings say, GOD blew us into a mud "mould". What if he passes on that ENERGY to our "mould" and life begins.  With life, there is death, as we know it. text: A 1500-year-old bible has been discovered in Turkey. Discovered in 2000, the book that contains purportedly the Gospel of Barnabas has been transferred by the Turkish government to the Ethnography Museum of Ankara with a police escort. Barnabas was a disciple of Christ, and in the work, claims that Jesus was not crucified, instead it says he ascended to heaven alive and Judas Iscariot was crucified in his place. Furthermore, the 1500-year-old bible states that Jesus Christ was not the son of God, but simply a prophet who passed on the word of God.

text: In The Holy Quran :  `Îsâ Ibn Maryam ( Arabic: عيسى, translit.: ʿĪsā ), known as Jesus in the New Testament, is considered to be a Messenger of God and al-Masih (the Messiah) in Islam :30 who was sent to guide the Children of Israel (banī isrā'īl) with a new scripture, al-Injīl (the Gospel). The belief that Jesus is a prophet is required in Islam, as it is for all prophets named in the Qur’an. This is reflected in the fact that he is clearly a significant figure in the Qur’an (appearing in 93 ayaat [or, verses]), though Noah, Adam and Moses appear with even greater frequency. It states that Jesus was born to Mary (Arabic: Maryam) as the result of virginal conception, a miraculous event which occurred by the decree of God (Arabic: Allah). To aid in his ministry to the Jewish people, Jesus was given the ability to perform miracles (such as healing the blind, bringing dead people back to life, etc.), all by the permission of God rather than of his own power. According to the Quran, Jesus, although appearing to have been crucified, was not killed by crucifixion or by any other means; instead, "God raised him unto Himself". Like all prophets in Islam, Jesus is considered a Muslim (i.e., one who submits to the will of God), as he preached that his followers should adopt the "straight path" as commanded by God. Islam rejects the Trinitarian Christian view that Jesus was God incarnate or the son of God, that he was ever crucified or resurrected, or that he ever atoned for the sins of mankind. The Quran says that Jesus himself never claimed any of these things, and it furthermore indicates that Jesus will deny having ever claimed divinity at the Last Judgment, and God will vindicate him. The Quran emphasizes that Jesus was a mortal human being who, like all other prophets, had been divinely chosen to spread God's message. Islamic texts forbid the association of partners with God (shirk), emphasizing a strict notion of monotheism (tawhīd). An alternative interpretation of this theology is held by Messianic Muslims.

text: From the Geneva: "Jer" 10:2  Thus saith the "?orde", LEARNE NOT THE WAY OF THE HEATHEN, & be not afraid for the signes of heauen, though the heathen be afraid of such.  "Jer" 10:3  For the customes of the people are vaine: for one cutteth a tree out of the forest (which is the worke of the handes of the carpenter) with the axe,  "Jer" 10:4  And another decketh it with siluer, and with golde: they fasten it with nailes, and hammers, that it fall not.   From the book Christianity Before Christ, by John G. Jackson:  Chapter III The Savior "God" Cults  Comparative hierologists (the comparative and historical study of religions) have discovered records of about thirty savior-"God" religions.  These cults spread over all the world in very remote times, but they show evidence of a common origin.  The various savior-"Gods" had the following similar traits:  1. They were born on or near Christ Mass/christmas. 2. Their mothers were virgins. 3. They were born in a cave or stable. 4. They worked for the salvation of humanity. 5. They were called saviors, mediators, healers, etc. 6. They were overcome by evil powers. 7. A descent into hell was made by them. 8. After being slain they arose from death and ascended to heaven at easter. 9. They founded religious institutions. 10. They were commemorated by eucharistic rites. 11. Many of these savior-"Gods" were believed to make a second coming to the world.  Of the thirty or so discovered, here are some of the most notable ones:  1. bel of babylonia 2. osiris of egypt 3. prometheus of greece 4. mithra of persia 5. krishna of india  Chapter IV Bel: The Babylonian Christ  In the British Museum there is an ancient tablet from Babylon, dating back to about 2000 B.C.  This document is a description of a passion play relating to the god bel.  (The same divinity was called baal (basket-baal, base-baal, foot-baal.........something I've added) among the ancient Hebrews.)  This dramatic performance consisted of ten acts, or scenes.  My additions/comments: These acts or scenes, are about the exact traits listed above.  There was a period of about four hundred years between when the last book of the "OT" was written (Malachi) and when the first book of that "NT" was started.  If YOU were there back then, what would you do...........to get saved?  Of course, you would follow one of the "religions" listed above. text: Muslims respect and revere Jesus (peace be upon him).  They consider him one of the greatest of God’s messengers to mankind.  The Quran confirms his virgin birth, and a chapter of the Quran is entitled ‘Maryam’ (Mary).  The Quran describes the birth of Jesus as follows:    (Remember) when the angels said, “O Mary, God gives you good news of a word from Him (God), whose name is the Messiah Jesus, son of Mary, revered in this world and the Hereafter, and one of those brought near (to God).  He will speak to the people from his cradle and as a man, and he is of the righteous.” She said, “My Lord, how can I have a child when no mortal has touched me?” He said, “So (it will be).  God creates what He wills.  If He decrees a thing, He says to it only, ‘Be!’ and it is.”  (Quran, 3:45-47)  Jesus was born miraculously by the command of God, the same command that had brought Adam into being with neither a father nor a mother.  God has said:    The case of Jesus with God is like the case of Adam.  He created him from dust, and then He said to him, “Be!” and he came into being.  (Quran, 3:59)  During his prophetic mission, Jesus performed many miracles.  God tells us that Jesus said:    “I have come to you with a sign from your Lord.  I make for you the shape of a bird out of clay, I breathe into it, and it becomes a bird by God’s permission.  I heal the blind from birth and the leper.  And I bring the dead to life by God’s permission.  And I tell you what you eat and what you store in your houses....”  (Quran, 3:49)  Muslims believe that Jesus was not crucified.  It was the plan of Jesus’ enemies to crucify him, but God saved him and raised him up to Him.  And the likeness of Jesus was put over another man.  Jesus’ enemies took this man and crucified him, thinking that he was Jesus.  God has said:    ...They said, “We killed the Messiah Jesus, son of Mary, the messenger of God.” They did not kill him, nor did they crucify him, but the likeness of him was put on another man (and they killed that man)...  (Quran, 4:157)  Neither Muhammad  nor Jesus came to change the basic doctrine of the belief in one God, brought by earlier prophets, but rather to confirm and renew it.1

text: Es curioso. Los ateos militantes critican las interacciones de la iglesia y los dogmas religiosos en la vida pública, pero ellos hacen una verdadera y constante labor de contra-evangelización en los medios, en la calle, en el arte. Incluso tienen tiempo de entrar aquí sólo para cuestionar la veracidad de la vida de Jesús y mofarse de los cristianos. Hablan de lo que no saben, pero eso lo hacemos todos. Lo triste y lo preocupante para el conjunto de la sociedad es preguntarse, en pleno siglo XXI, cuando realmente la iglesia ya ni pincha ni corta y los valores cristianos están denostados, ¿qué obtienen estos activistas pro-ateos? ¿Qué beneficio y regocijo interior encuentran al convencer a los que creen de que todo es mentira? ¿Qué satisfacción encuentran, en definitiva, en la decepción de los creyentes? Para mi la respuesta es muy sencilla: es como cuando en el colegio suspendías un examen, pero si todos los demás niños lo hacían, de alguna forma te sentías mejor. Ya no pueden decir que la iglesia influye, que prohíbe, que limita... ya no queda ni rastro de eso. Sólo un vacío del alma y una necesidad de sentirse acompañados en la nada existencial. Y si hay alguien que me pueda dar otra razón sin caer en los tópicos de siempre, por favor que me responda. Que me explique qué necesidad tiene alguien de entrar a esta página para ofender los sentimientos religiosos de los demás.

text: Day in and day out, nothing ever changes, unless you make the change, I sometimes think what it would be like to be someone like Bill Gates or any other Billionaire, but I think their lives are not a happy life, sometimes I think that they too, wish they could just fly away to somewhere where they could find peace within themselves, and peace all around them. " I am merely a representation of what you are willing to believe" In this saying you will come to understand, that this is how the world see's others. But the truth is far more amazing indeed. Now ask yourself. "Who is the chosen one?" Answer......... YOU...... All of you, even the cat and dog, and all the other creatures that make up this Planet, and all the creatures throughout the Universe. We are all chosen by the source of life (God) we are all the Messiah, it's just the religious organisations will have you believe other wise, in order to stop you being free, for true freedom comes from the source of life (God) then through your heart and mind.   The human mind is of two parts, the conscious mind and the subconscious mind. The conscious mind lives in our brains, but our subconscious mind lives outside our body, in fact, the subconscious mind is our true self that is part of God. To know what perfection is, is impossible, but it's right in front of us the whole time, that being the subconscious mind, the source of life (God). We live in a world where our conscious mind is our main mind we use to think with, but our subconscious mind holds the secrets to our true selves that being part of the source of life (God).   When it is time for our body to die, our subconscious mind becomes the conscious mind and we become one with the source of life (God). It is interesting to note, that when people have a brain operation if they are conscious throughout the operation which in some cases they do an operation while the patient is still conscious, the surgeon will ask the patient to speak while the surgeon touches parts of the patients brain, the patient can not speak, but after the operation patients often say that they could think for themselves with no trouble at all while the operation was being carried out. So there is proof that the subconscious mind lives outside our bodies, but is connected to our conscious mind.   The subconscious mind is also connected to the highest dimension, the source of life (God) as well, but not our conscious mind. Our conscious mind live in this dimension which is filled with doubt and disbelief.Believe This.... Ultimately, when you view it from the highest dimension, there is no time and no space, there is no future and no past, it all is occurring in one fascinating moment of expression, but time is an illusion that has purpose.   To answer the question about animals having a subconscious mind that is connected to the source of life (God)? The answer to this is yes. Also Bugs, Fish and Birds all have a subconscious mind that is part of source (source of life God). And if you think that this planet is the only planet that has conscious minds that are connected to the subconscious mind that is the source of life (God), you got another thing coming, you can bet your bottom dollar that the universe is teeming with consciousness in the forms of whatever the subconscious mind source of life (God) made.   About wanting and getting things you like and want. Believe from your subconscious mind that you already have them, and it will happen.   The Conscious mind is a mind that is victimized by hate and suffering in order to get along, but remember, the religious organisations killed Jesus, who was a man that was one with the source of life (God) and even to this day, the religious organisations will kill whoever stops them from keeping this man made power. But the Subconscious Mind source of life (GOD) from time to time will down load wisdom on whom The Subconscious Mind chooses.... The source of life (God) is like the wind, you do not know when it will come, or for whom it will come, but when it comes to you, you will be filled with awe and greatness and Love. The conscious Mind can never know the Subconscious mind if the conscious Mind lives by the religious organisations belief systems, only when you free yourself from the religious organisations grip will you be one with the higher Subconscious Mind, the source of life, your true self, (God).

text: I can't even watch a trailer of a movie about my lord and savoir Jesus Christ because of all the HATE spouted by Christians, Muslims, and disbelievers..  humble yourselves people. I know one thing for certain... no one on this thread is the Son of God, and thus does not speak for him.  The Parable of the Pharisee and the Tax Collector.  9 He then addressed this parable to those who were convinced of their own righteousness and despised everyone else.c 10 “Two people went up to the temple area to pray; one was a Pharisee and the other was a tax collector. 11 The Pharisee took up his position and spoke this prayer to himself, ‘O God, I thank you that I am not like the rest of humanity—greedy, dishonest, adulterous—or even like this tax collector. 12 I fast twice a week, and I pay tithes on my whole income.’d 13 But the tax collector stood off at a distance and would not even raise his eyes to heaven but beat his breast and prayed, ‘O God, be merciful to me a sinner.’e 14 I tell you, the latter went home justified, not the former; for everyone who exalts himself will be humbled, and the one who humbles himself will be exalted.”f    As to my personal opinion:   Jesus IS THE FINAL COVENANT, who came not to cast down or replace the Law of Moses... but to succeed and perfect it. The two great commandments that contain the whole law of God are:  Thou shalt love the Lord thy God with thy whole heart, and with thy whole soul, and with thy whole mind, and with thy whole strength  Thou shalt love thy neighbor as thyself.  The first three Commandments are summed up by the First Great Commandment Jesus gives, to love and honor God with all that we are.  The next Seven are summed up in the Second Great Commandment Jesus gave us, to love our neighbor as ourselves.  To do these two things is surely worth more than all the sacrifices and burnt offerings one could make. I pray that you live a life of true love of the glory of God, cherish each other, especially your enemies, for if we only loved those who love us... what reward is there in that?  Pray fore peace please... beware of the temptations this Lent, the same that the Devil used to tempt Jesus Pleasure, Fame and Power are temptations to us all that we must overcome to enter the Kingdom of God.   Peace be upon you all... Muslims (Sunni and Shia, Jews, Buddhists, Hindus, non-believers, Christians and all the People of God, may he call us ALL home to love and serve His will. He will reign, and His lamb will rule.   But enough words: One of my favorite quotes that reflects how powerful Christ's perfect example of life is in changing the world through his loving EXAMPLE instead of force:  "Preach the Gospel at all times and when necessary use words." - St. Francis of Assisi

text: "I am a son of God," well there’s the whole thing in a nutshell. If you read the King James Bible… You will see in italics, in front of the words "son of God," THE "son of God." Most people think the italics are for emphasis. They’re not. The italics indicate words interpolated [as preference] by the translators. You will not find that in the Greek. In the Greek it says, a son of God. It seems to me here perfectly plain. That Jesus has got it in the back of his mind that this isn't something peculiar to himself. So when he says, "I am the Way, no Man comes to the Father but by me." This "I am" this "Me" is the divine in us. We are sons of, or of the nature of God. Manifestations of the divine. This discovery is the gospel. That is the Good News. But this has been perpetually repressed throughout the history of Western religion…
